The paper deals with distributed graph algorithms and their complexity, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The concept of locally checkable labelings (LCLs) is a fundamental topic in distributed graph algorithms and is closely related to the study of graph theory and combinatorics (cs.DS). The paper also discusses graph coloring, which is a classic problem in theoretical computer science and falls under the category of Computational Complexity (cs.CC). The study of LCLs and graph coloring also involves game theory and the analysis of strategic behavior, which falls under the category of Game Theory and Economic Theory (cs.GT). Finally, the paper presents new results and insights into the complexity of partial graph coloring, which is a topic in machine learning and data analysis, falling under the category of Learning (cs.LG).
